BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:voPa0E8Zom-kfOl59ZjBv
SUMMARY:Member Family Day: Animal Intelligence
DTSTAMP:20260409T031203Z
DTSTART:20260411T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:SAM members\, don't have a room with a view booked this spring 
	break? Kick off your staycation with A Room for Animal Intelligence. Get y
	our free tickets to visit the museum on April 11 \\(or anytime through Apr
	il 19\\) and enjoy enriching activities. This is a whole new way of seeing
	 the animal world curated by Pam McClusky. Come face-to-face with 100 anim
	als from around the globe\, rendered at jaw- dropping scale. We're talking
	 the largest wolf\, mouse\, and mosquito you've ever laid eyes on. The kid
	s won't stop talking about it-and honestly\, neither will you. Grab a bite
	 from the Shooby Doo pop-up café \\(11 am-3 pm\\)\, listen to live jazz cu
	rated by Seattle Jazz Fellowship \\(11 am-2 pm\\)\, and join a public coll
	ection tour that includes a stop in A Room for Animal Intelligence \\(11:3
	0 am\\). 10 am-5 pm Build a Beast Brotman Forum Build your very own beast 
	using hand-carved animal stamps created by artist Brian Lane. Pen Pal with
	 an Animal A Room for Animal Intelligence gallery Choose your favorite ani
	mal in the exhibition to be pen pals with and write to them using the stat
	ionary provided in the gallery. Who knows! You might just hear back . . . 
	Wolf Haven International Booth Brotman Forum Visit the Wolf Haven Internat
	ional booth to learn more about wolves and the organization's efforts to r
	estore near-extinct species. Animal-themed Scavenger Hunt A Room for Anima
	l Intelligence Pick up a scavenger hunt created by SAM Docent\, David Turn
	er\, from the Ticketing Desk and embark on your adventure to discover the 
	wit\, wonder\, and wisdom of A Room for Animal Intelligence! 10:30 am | Co
	mplimentary Pastries for Members Arnold Board Room Start your morning with
	 a delicious pastry made by Shooby Doo Catering \\(while supplies last\\).
	 11-11:30 am | Illustrated Storytime with Julie Kim Arnold Board Room Brin
	g your little one to experience the artistic magic of an illustrated anima
	l storytime by artist Julie Kim. 11:30 am-noon | Selfies with Sammy the Ca
	mel A Room for Animal Intelligence gallery Step into the gallery after sto
	rytime to take a selfie with Sammy the Camel! 1-1:30 pm | Wolves 101 Talk 
	Arnold Board Room Learn all about wolves from a globally recognized wolf s
	anctuary\, Wolf Haven International\, at this engaging talk for kids! 3-4 
	pm | Wolves in the Pacific Northwest Talk Arnold Board Room Learn all abou
	t wolves of the Pacific Northwest and what it takes to restore near-extinc
	t populations from Wolf Haven International. Sun Apr 12-Sun Apr 19 Can't m
	ake the kick-off event on April 11? Visit any open day during spring break
	 week to write to an animal\, build a beast and go on a scavenger hunt. Pl
	us\, curator Pam McClusky will be leading a few short tours of the exhibit
	ion \\(3 pm on Apr 15\, 16 and 17\\) and all public tours that week will s
	top in A Room for Animal Intelligence.  These activities are free to membe
	rs and 40% off admission for your guests! Simply reserve museum tickets fo
	r April 11. Or visit between the 12 and 19 to celebrate A Room for Animal 
	Intelligence with us.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/mem
	ber-family-day-animal-intelligence/18529573/2026-04-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday
	 - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/member-family-day-animal-
	intelligence/18529573/2026-04-11T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:SO11lU1A8_bFhIjwakwc8
SUMMARY:Family Saturday | Get Ready for Baby Rave
DTSTAMP:20260409T031203Z
DTSTART:20260411T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Gear up for Baby Rave by transforming everyday items into vibra
	nt wearable works of art with guidance from teaching artist\, Claudia Vill
	alobos! Upcycle materials including cardboard\, fabric scraps\, and repurp
	osed embellishments to design wings\, crowns\, skirts and other wearable p
	ieces that sparkle\, reflect light\, and show off your family's creativity
	. Ideal for kids and grown-ups to create together. Then spend your afterno
	on with your family exploring art and the natural environment. This progra
	m takes place outside at the Olympic Sculpture Park on the covered north t
	errace of the PACCAR Pavilion. Walk-ins welcome on a first-come\, first-se
	rved basis.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/family-saturd
	ay-get-ready-for-baby-rave/18529076/2026-04-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts 
	& Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/family-saturday-get-ready
	-for-baby-rave/18529076/2026-04-11T00
LOCATION:Olympic Sculpture Park\, 2901 Western Ave\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:g9_r6mar7SIEgKQNFtI3R
SUMMARY:Eric-Paul Riege: ojo|-|ólǫ́
DTSTAMP:20260409T031203Z
DTSTART:20260411T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:ojo|-|ólǫ́ is an exhibition of recent and newly commissioned w
	ork by Diné artist Eric-Paul Riege \\(b. 1994\, Na’nízhoozhí \\[Gallup\, N
	ew Mexico\\]\\) that includes sculpture\, textile\, collage\, and video\, 
	activated by moments of performance. Across this work\, Riege combines cus
	tomary Diné practices of weaving\, silversmithing\, and beading with conte
	mporary cultural forms\, exploring Diné cosmology\, the history of Euro-Am
	erican trading posts in and adjacent to the Navajo Nation\, and the notion
	 of “authenticity” as a value marker of Indigenous art and craft.\n\nDevel
	oped in partnership between the Henry and The Bell Gallery at Brown Univer
	sity\, ojo|-|ólǫ́ emerged from Riege’s material research with Navajo coll
	ections housed at Brown’s Haffenreffer Museum of Anthropology and the Univ
	ersity of Washington’s Burke Museum of Natural History and Culture. The re
	sulting body of work celebrates the ancestral knowledge and labor containe
	d within Indigenous-made objects\, while investigating the role of museums
	 and other institutions in the dissemination and dispossession of knowledg
	e about Indigenous cultures. For his tactile and modular soft sculptures\,
	 Riege employs exaggerated scale and combines synthetic and natural materi
	als to playfully question ideas of authenticity and Indigenous artistic pr
	oduction. Processes of making and remaking embody a living practice of exc
	hange that draws together webs of connection across time and space.\n\nThe
	 exhibition also includes objects from the Burke collection displayed alon
	gside assorted ephemera from Riege’s own home and studio. The resulting no
	n-hierarchal display blurs lines between past and present\, private and pu
	blic\, and real and fake\, animating the dynamism and dimensionality of In
	digenous cultures and identities. ojo|-|ólǫ́ invites collective reflection
	 on the practices of institutions that have accumulated Indigenous art\, w
	hile advancing a call for Indigenous cultural resurgence in the present an
	d toward our shared future.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/detai
	ls/eric-paul-riege-ojo-o-l/18307676/2026-04-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts 
	& Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/eric-paul-riege-ojo-o-l/1
	8307676/2026-04-11T00
LOCATION:Henry Art Gallery\, 15th Ave NE & 41st St\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
